  "prompt": "What is the difference between adding and committing in Git?",
  "response": "In Git, `adding` and `committing` are two distinct actions that are part of the process of saving changes to the repository.\n\n1. **Adding (`git add`)**:\n   - When you modify files in your working directory, those changes are not automatically included in the next commit. To include them, you need to add them to the staging area.\n   - `git add` is the command used to add changes to the staging area. This indicates that you want these changes to be part of the next commit.\n   - You can add specific files (`git add filename`) or all changes in the current directory (`git add .`).\n   - The staging area is where you prepare changes that you intend to commit. You can think of it as a \"waiting room\" for changes.\n\n2. **Committing (`git commit`)**:\n   - Once changes are in the staging area, you need to commit them to the local repository.\n   - `git commit` is the command used to create a snapshot of the changes in the staging area. This snapshot is saved in the repository with a unique identifier (commit hash).\n   - When committing, you usually provide a commit message to describe the changes (`git commit -m \"your commit message\"`). This helps in understanding what changes were made and why.\n   - Committing is a more permanent action compared to adding. It saves the changes to the repository history, making them part of the project\u2019s history.\n\nIn summary, `git add` is used to add changes to the staging area in preparation for a commit, while `git commit` is used to permanently record those staged changes in the repository\u2019s history.",
